Here's a great example why credit reports are not reliable, or a
measurement of one's trustworthiness. Especially since the reporters
themselves can't be trusted.

http://www.businessweek.com/bwdaily/dnflash/content/oct2007/db2007103...

To sum it up; a consumer had a credit card, which was included in a
bankruptcy. But Capital One kept reporting the card as an open card,
with a balance, and (I assume) late. Despite numerous calls and letters,
Capital One never fixed the error. Consumer ended up having to pay
the balance in order to be able to get a mortgage.

The story even goes on to tell that debt collectors buy discharged
debts, and then try to collect them. And, of course, report them to
the credit bureaus in the process.
