It's not that simple. This is how understood it. Traditionally, banks
had trouble because they were borrowing short (deposits), and lending
long (mortgages). So that created an imbalance of lengths of the various
accounts.

That's why they started packaging and selling mortgages. And so nowadays
it's pretty common to have your mortgage sold, even many times during
its life. So therefore the bank isn't really on the hook for it for
a very long time.
