I am not even sure that with this latest fiasco, as with previous,
though smaller ones, as long as a lot of  cash kept coming in up
front, which it did when the mortgages were created, those who should
have been responsible, decided to look at sales figures and potential
income down the line, rather than do a true evaluation of risk.

These are like ponzi schemes with CEOs perfectly happy to take the
benefits and praise and accounting companies signing off on it all. I
cannot believe that no one with experience in this area did not
foresee problems down the road. Basically they were ignored for short
term gain.

There were more than a few warning signs about the housing bubble, but
of course the Fed Reserve's pet rat, Greenspan, was either dense or
reprehensible.

Do I think a lot of these losses are caused by crooked dealing on the
part of the mortgage companies? Like the S&amp;L scandals or in businesses
like Enron and Anderson? I am not sure.

Either everyone selling these mortgages to those who would likely be
unable to pay them off when the adjustable  rates went up was so young
that they had no memory or knowledge of the vagaries of the market
place (just as many folks who put every sent into the dot.com bubble,
never believing that the numbers would collapse), or they were trained
not to take such risks into account, or those in management who *did*
understand what could happen, figured they and their own company would
float over it all and take the money and run. Only they tripped.

Pushing  these sub prime mortgages met a lot of sales goals, earned a
lot of commissions and initial cash and now there are a lot of
mortgage servicers out of jobs, whole companies gone under,  homes in
foreclosure, and billions up in smoke.

None of that falls under the usual &quot;assumed risk&quot; of the mortgage and
credit business. Greed and/or stupidity on the part of the mortgage
companies, complete or in some cases head-in-the-sand ignorance on the
part of  homeowners who trusted (yes, very mistakenly so) the banks
when qualified.   When all the lenders are qualifying these people for
huge mortgages with little or no money down, the borrowers do get
lulled (I am not defending all of them) into thinking that is the way
*all* mortgaging works and has always worked.

An economic bubble built on a house of cards.

Boron

